{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1945"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1945"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.22,0.48,0.02,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1945"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68722"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman is admitted to hospital for an elective cholecystectomy. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker and consumes four standard alcoholic drinks per week. Her pre-operative serum biochemistry does not show any abnormalities. The surgical procedure is uneventful, she is recovering well and does not report any neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the day after the cholecystectomy, she is alert and orientated. Her pulse rate is 66/min, respiratory rate 16/min and blood pressure 110/80 mmHg. She has moist mucus membranes, a central capillary refill of 2 seconds, normal skin turgor, no peripheral oedema and her breath sounds are vesicular throughout both lung fields on auscultation. Post-operative results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u2022 Sodium 128 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr\u003E\u2022 Other electrolytes within normal limits\u003Cbr\u003E\u2022 Serum osmolality 260 mOsm/kg (285-295)\u003Cbr\u003E\u2022 Urine osmolality 202 mOsm/kg (\u003C100)\u003Cbr\u003E\u2022 Urine sodium 40 mmol/L (\u003C20)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertonic 3% saline","0.9% sodium chloride","Fluid restriction","5% dextrose","Vasopressin receptor antagonist"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause for this patient\u0027s hyponatraemia is syndrome of inappropriate anti-diuretic hormone secretion (\u003Cstrong\u003ESIADH\u003C/strong\u003E), with examination findings suggestion euvolaemia and biochemistry demonstrating reduced serum osmolality (hypotonic hyponatraemia), increased urine osmolality and increased urine sodium. Note that for completeness, thyroid dysfunction and adrenal insufficiency should also be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESIADH has a wide range of causes including surgery. \u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line management for SIADH, and the severity of the fluid restriction can be titrated depending on the response to the serum sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered in cases of acute, severe symptomatic hyponatraemia - the administration of which requires close monitoring and usually intensive care admission. The patient in the stem was asymptomatic and there were no neurological findings of note on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous fluids such as \u003Cstrong\u003E0.9% sodium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E5% dextrose\u003C/strong\u003E are not appropriate management options in SIADH, although a crystalloid fluid such as 0.9% sodium chloride may be appropriate in a case of hypovolaemic hyponatraemia (not SIADH).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Evasopressin receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E such as Tolvaptan can correct the serum sodium in a proportion of patients with hyponatraemia, they should not be considered a first-line management option for the management of SIADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fluid restriction should be the first-line management option for SIADH."],"references":["Simon, EE. Hyponatremia - Practice Essentials, Pathophysiology, Epidemiology. In: Medscape [online]. 2019. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/242166-overview.","Thomas, CP. Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion (SIADH) - Treatment \u0026 Management. In: Medscape. 2019. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/246650-treatment#d1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68722"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1945"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68722"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-08T13:15:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-08T13:17:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1945"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84182"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a